,Recommended,294100,25425448,"Posted: 9 September, 2016",all,Evord,"This game is fun and addictive. The description is spot on. Its like Sims+Dwarf Fortress+Space. Totally awesome. Its dedication to making meaning out of the little things is truely exemplary. Running a colony is not easy and keeping everyone alive despite themselves is challenging.The game gives you a lot of tools and a lot of problems and you have to figure the rest out. Its a lot of fun IMO to do so. Every colony I start has new challenges, complexities, and dies a different way LOL.See, your colonists are flawed people. They have had hard lives and lived through a lot. Everyone has their preferences, quirks, strengths and weaknesses. They are also people, not drones. They want nice things... and get unhapoy when forced to toil endlessly slave labor conditions.Its just as much about the people as it is about progression.To understand, let me tell you a story.This story is mostly about a teenager named Fay. Once there was a crashed colony shop and it had 3 survivors. The other two colonists are Erin and Taya. But Erin and Taya are only important in that they are militantly opposed to cooking for themselves. Perhaps their parents only ever ate out and Erin and Taya deeply believe that they cannot even learn to cook.Fay though, Fay can cook. Not well however. She is in fact, terrible at it and will likely never be good. Despite this, Fay has to cook for everyone. Its largely self defense because Erin and Taya refuse to cook. So either Fay cooks or she eats uncooked rice and boar corpses.And so the colony lived on...or it would have of not for Fay's crucial addiction to alcohol. She is massively alcoholic in fact, but there's no booze at all on the crashed colony. Prolonged sobriety is intolerable for Fay and so, once a month, she has a mental breakdown from withdrawal. Usually this means she just flings off her clothing and wanders in the woods for a while.It also means that, once a month, Erin and Taya have no one to cook for them. I have no sympathy for their week long starvation. The lack of proper work getting done during that time is deplorable however. As Erin and Taya also have mental break downs after a week of eaten raw-rice covered frozen squirel corpses, I start to care less and less about curing Fay's alcoholism and more about just getting the woman a drink.The opportunity arises when a trader comes through with beer. Fay trades generously for said beer and her mental stability improves dramaticlly with every swig. For a while, meals get cooked and work gets done in the colony. I have hope for the winter.Until Taya's mom, Raven, shows up. Injured and crawling to us through the wilds, she is rescued by Taya. Even better, Raven can cook! The colony is saved! Stability at last!And then she promptly dies of a stomache infection....in Taya's bed no less. We tried to amputate her stomach to save her, but the operation failed. Not that success would have been success.Taya is destroyed by this event, understandably. In her grief, she steals all the colony's beer and drinks herself sick. Can you blame the poor lady?Immediatly, a deprived Fay plunges into withdrawal once again. She breaks quickly and runs off naked into the winter night. It doesn't end well. The colony looks doomed at this point. Taya and Erin stare at the stove that puzzles them so as they munch on a mad racoon that is dead on their table.But lucky stars above! A new cook wanders in and wishes to join the colony! It's a godsend. We are saved!Before the new cook can set down her things, Erin and Taya go nuts from eating frozen raw rice and dead bandits. Super nuts. The Shining nuts.Berserk with hunger and probably rabies, Erin and Taya kill their savoir chef before fatally mauling each other.Erin dies atop the corpses of her fellows. Inches from the unused stove and stockpile of food that could have saved them all. If only she'd believed in herself and tried to cook. Just once...So yeah, this game rocks. Its hard but hilarious. You'll be balancing the most ridiculous, yet natural, problems while constantly expanding your abilities and liabilites.Other important facts1. No multiplayer2. No victory conditions, you play forever and just have to roll your own win.3. Combat is simple yet strangly, deeply tactical and statisfying.4. There's also factions and regional politics to manage.5. The UI is a little intimidating, but ultimately its not hard to use once you grok a few critical tools (like zones).I paid $30 for this on early access, which I normally NEVER would do. Its been a great purchase so far. Many lulz and many facepalms. Goddamnit Fay, Erin, and Taya. ^_^"
