76561198038867851,Recommended,294100,25277665,"Posted: 31 August, 2016",all,Rhace,"I wish I could say my Rimworld story was like everyone elses, where a group of nobodies makes a name for themselves and lasts a few years until that badass Alamo shootout kills everyone in a blaze of glory. I wish I could say I raised my group of scavengers into a force to be reckoned with, with guns and turrets and state of the art facilities. I wish my experience was like that.It was not.My experience was, to put it bluntly, harrowing.I had chosen the start where you start as a single individual, with good equipment and a history of living a luxury life on a Glitterworld. I was a woman barely in her twenties, who had fought a war shortly and had a good hand at shooting while also being able to build fortifications in record time. My name was Engie, and this was going to be a great experience full of adventure and riches.I had landed near a mountainous region, and decided to make a highly defensible position based on single doors and lots of turrets. I only made rooms that were directly within the mountain, with my farms outside in the natural sunlight and weather. The first few months were quiet, with a few settlers coming in to join the newly crowned Daedalus Outpost and make themselves a home made by the sweat of their own brow. Everything was peachy and perfect, with an emphasis on helping one another and making sacrafices so that the greater good would prosper.After awhile the raiders would come and attempt to enslave or steal, but the sentries were always there to defend the settlers while Engie and a select few made shots with pulse rifles and slugthrowers. No matter what they did, the multi-layered defense system was always there to protect and keep the populace safe. Eventually, they stopped altogether. At first, we thought it was because our system was impenetrable. We were completely wrong, and we realized it when a green haze came over the horizon and everything in it's vicnity started to die out. A toxic fallout had come to our region, and we had no idea how long this was going to last.I won't say what happened during that fallout, because to recount such an event is to fill this story with even more dread than what is to come. I can only imagine the raiders who came in the dead of winter, noting how everything was cold and lifless around the mountain. They had come prepared for a fight against the sentries, but all of them were shut down from what seemed to be a lack of power. The raider burst through one of the doors, and started to try and find the residents, wary of an ambush or surprise fire. They found the door to the walk-in freezer, and opened it.One can only imagine what they thought, when they saw the last resident of Daedalus Outpost.In there sat Engie, the original survivor and the leader of this group of individuals. This wasn't the founder that the raiders had heard stories about, with her bravado and deadshot aim that was the bane of attackers everywhere. This was a much more harrowing version, covered in blood and clothed in a parka that was undoubtedly made from human skin. Surrounding her was a copious amount of blood and meat, which may have not been easily identifiable if one of the original residents hadn't been strewn across the butcher's table, missing limbs and body chunks.When she saw the raiders, Engie screamed and charged at them with only her bare fists. Obviously having been driven mad by the necessity to eat her friends, she went towards the raiders with a desire for more meat, more food to survive this decaying land of death. She didn't even make it halfway towards them when a bolt went straight through her eye and out the back of her head.The raiders left empty handed, running out of the mountain to go back to their homes where such a terrifying experience may be forgotten. Daedalus Outpost was abandoned, a once prospering settlement that turned into a dead zone of legend. The only clue as to what may have happened there was deep in the mountain, where a freezer room held the remains of a savage and the meat of her friends."
