,Recommended,294100,24426241,"Posted: 20 July, 2016",all,Ultric,"I'll be honest, I'm not the biggest fan of this genre. I haven't played much dwarf fortress, games like Towns, Gnomoria and Craft The World usually elicit a single long playthrough that, though enjoyable, usually concludes my time with the game whenever I have everything unlocked.RimWorld has been pretty much the opposite. I've played about 5-6 times already, lost my colony to various things, whether it infection wiping out my people, raiders gunning down all but one of my colonists and leaving the surivor to wander around the compound with crippling depression or whatever...it doesn't matter. I just start up a new colony and go at it again.A little reccomendation: If you play games like Xcom or stuff like that with iron man off, don't do so with this game. Go in the way it's meant to be played, it's surprisingly easy to go through with restarting, and I haven't had any bugs so far. Honestly, I think the best thing this game does is remove character creation. Clicking random until you get people who generally fit what you need kinda detaches you from them, meaning that when they inevitably die, you're fine with just going again (at least for me). I still haven't had any playthroughs that I'm incredibly proud of, but so far, every loss has taught me something and I feel like I now have a really efficient method of starting thte game.One universal piece of advice: Build graves as soon as somebody on the map dies, friend or foe, and get all bodies buried ASAP. Just trust me."
