,Recommended,294100,26180546,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,König der Hunde,"Currently at 170 hours.I only play Permadeath (no saves except on exit), Classic Storyteller, Some Challenge difficulty, Crashlanded Scenario (3 colonists basic scenario) and I accept every random choice they make for me (planet seed, starting location, colonist stats, etc) no matter how good or bad. This playstyle has given me so many wildly different narratives, stories of triumph, defeat, sadness, and unexpected joy.This is a game about the journey, not the finish line.I still have not had a successful colony to date. My most successful one lasted probably about 30-40 gameplay hours, which ultimately fell to an unchecked infestation while dealing with attrition and a seige. I sat in silence, respectfully released all my animals, and watched in abject detatchment as my legless prisoner eventually succumbed to simultaneous starvation and infection. He died alone, in extreme pain, and surrounded by the clattering claws of murderous bugs scraping his cell walls. I like to think his slip into unconciousness saved him from the horrific fate that awaited.The game looks basic, but the interactions between everything are masterfully crafted. You will find yourself having to make hard choices that will really make you question your own values in life. The AI is a masterful story-teller.I can't express this enough: the real enjoyment from this game comes from the meta story. It's a great colony builder, and you can micro-manage so much that it will really satisfy those OCD control issues, but you have to learn to accept losses. It's all about risk management, time management, and resource management.One of the most stressful, but satisfying gameplay experiences I've had in a long time.My only advice: learn to accept losses and failure."
