76561198087006743,Recommended,294100,30493010,Posted: 13 March,all,Sophikachu,"This game is fun, intuitive and smart. It follows some basic, simple rules and concepts that allow for near-infinite variation in scenarios and let you fight your own way, coming up with innovative solutions for different issues. This means you can play the game in a myriad of different ways, keeping it interesting and fresh. Tired of fighting waves of attackers? Try the sea ice challenge and survive on your guts alone (and probably those of the enemies who unwittingly attacked you in -150C temperature). Want to just create a miniature empire that is exquisitely ordered and tweaked to perfection? Play in base builder mode and go for it. Want to see what it would be like if everything were just coming at you all the time? Randy Random is your guy. The updates are promising; but the game as is is already quite satisfying, and when you get bored of it there's always the (thousands of??) mods out there that offer improvements to various facets of the game. The game is obviously not perfect (there are some annoying tricks that will take you ages to figure out; you don't feel much of a connection to your little survivor buddies; some things such as the animals have to be tweaked to make a bit more sense to invest in) but I would absolutely recommend it."
76561198013132245,Recommended,294100,30332820,Posted: 5 March,all,huminado,"Yes buy it.It still has very minor issues in the day to day gameplay.  It has a good balance between planning and execution, with random events taking place provided by which storyteller you choose.  I.e. the storyteller (apparently) provides the non-deterministic events in the world, which can range from pirate raids or lunar eclipses to the wildlife going crazy.It seems to play like a D20 game.The Good:- Characters have to sleep each day - which usually means hitting fast forward.  This provides a casual feeling to the game - the game is not rushed.- It might even be the most casual ""chill"" game I can remember.  You can pause the clock at any moment or revert to an old save.  So even when things are getting heavy you can think through what needs to happen.- The game setting is living in the wild and pulling together a survival plan in the midst of the storyteller generating random events.  It's very easy-going this way -- not like Prison Architect which was too heavy and dark for me.- Grizzly bears seem to just eat berries.  Now you know storyteller will make them go crazy at any moment - so try to figure out a way to deal with them.The Bad:- The price feels high before you buy it.  So it might take longer before many people try this game.- The game could provide more pointers.  ""Just look it up on the Wiki.""  I suppose if you're hardcore you will want to figure everything out - but this is the blurry line between gameplay-based enjoyment and arbitrary recipe search-space Easter Egg hunting.- There's no demo.  You can watch youtube videos all day - you'll think this is a Dwarf fortress thing like I did, but it's not, and all the videos don't do the game justice.  A demo would have helped me get over the price hump.As it is this game is easily worth the asking price.  Listen - you have 2 hours to figure it out - if you still want a refund, you'll know after first hour."
