,Recommended,294100,25613587,"Posted: 20 September, 2016",all,shellgames,Amazing.Addicting.Yes.
,Recommended,294100,25625551,"Posted: 21 September, 2016",all,Auruko,"I have always loved base building and strategy games.  While acting as the all-seeing overlord I would come up with elaborate story arcs, develop relationships and connections where there were none.  I imagined individual events were part of a larger story, even if those events didn't have any lasting repercussions.  I would mold my decisions and playing style on those previous events, even if my pawns didn't remember.Rimworld has taken those acts that I loved (even before I realized what I loved about them) and turned them up to 11.  By taking those random events and giving them real world weight and consequences Rimworld develops storytelling in games to a level that I didn't even think was possible.  Yes, there are carefully crafted stories in games that are doled out in controlled segments, delivering a nice, neat package from beginning to end.  Rimworld is anything but neat.  You will be constantly blindsided, forced to overcome insurmountable odds as the world stacks its forces against you and your little colony.  As you try to cut out your place in the world and simply survive you will fight maneating animals (be they turtles or bears), raider attacks, heat waves, famine, fires, love and heartbreak, new colonists, death within your ranks, and scores of other events that never unfold the same way twice.  All of this layered over the individual interactions between each of the colonists and their traits, quirks, shortcomings, and triumphs.  By creating a giant sandbox over a spiderweb of interactions Tynan has given us the greatest story generator I have come across to date.  And it all comes across as genuine, since you aren't suspending disbelief in a storytelling style that maybe doesn't completely agree with you for whatever reason.  You are simply given the events, make your decisions, and live with how the world and your colonists have reacted.Yes the systems can be complex, the interactions obtuse, and you will feel like things are spiraling out of control (they probably are) but as you learn the game's mechanics and how to cope with each obstacle, you make it farther through each playthrough, the stories get deeper, your losses hurt you more and your triumphs have even more value.  And just when you think everything is lost, you reduce your scope, dig in, and move the story forward with what you have.I can't recommend this game enough.  If you have the patience to learn the systems, accept the hardships you are handed, and make the best with what you have, you will be rewarded with some of the most memorable moments in gaming that you have had in years.  A+"
