,Recommended,294100,30114013,Posted: 22 February,all,Skeletor Jesus,"TL;DR: Buy this game if it remotely interests you, you will not regret it. Except maybe don't buy it if you like your social and/or professional life.Allow me to tell you the tale of my first game:Three colonists awake to the sounds of explosions and alarms, in a panic they manage to make it to the escape pods. Of a ship of hundreds, they are the only ones to make it out alive. Those three were the engaged couple Lowe and Ceti, and a stranger. James was a counselor in his previous life, while Ceti a geologist. They weren't exactly a picture perfect match, but they were deeply in love and planned on getting married on a whole new world to begin their new lives together. Mushinto, the stranger was a hunter and former gang member - he never talked about his past, but the knife scar on his torso and gunshot scar on his arm said enough. Somewhere along the way, Mushinto managed to befriend a Yorkshire Terrier that he named Don and develop serious alcoholism. Upon first setting down, they set up a single large building, in order to escape the elements. After doing that, a couple rooms were added - so that the engaged couple may sleep together in peace, and they wouldn't disturb Mushinto at night. After the living arrangements had been settled, the illustrious group set up a couple farm patches, in order to grow rice and potatoes (Mark Watney would be proud). About one season later, Ceti's sister Glenn arrived! What luck! This is a good time to mention that Mushinto was getting quite close with Ceti - he attempted to romance her a number of times. As far as I can tell, she rejected him every time, so Mushinto turned to what little booze he had with him. Somehow Lowe never noticed, or if he did, he never acted on it. Mushinto and Glenn immediately hit it off on the wrong foot, becoming rivals quite quickly. They were never meant to be as she was a child spy turned machine collector and an ugly one at that, so Mushinto treated her quite awfully. Probably due to his withdrawals at not being able to brew more alcohol. The next season was spent expanding the settlement and doing some basic research. Sometime around late Summer, the settlers realized they did not have any parkas - so they desperately set up a cotton patch. Alas, they would not grow enough cotton before the weather started to change for the worse. Fighting off numerous animal and raider attacks, the settlers somehow managed to survive until Fall when a fifth arrived! The booms and smoke trail gave off the telltale signs of a crashing escape pod. Ceti was immediately dispatched to go rescue the lone survivor, Diver. It turns out that Diver was a former mercenary! Her skills would come in handy many times during raids and wild animal attacks. As the weather changed for the colder during fall, everything was looking good. The colony was expanding to add a few houses for the colonists, so they wouldn't have to live in the wooden main building, there was a massive supply of food (more than enough for three Winters!), and there were enough colonists to do all the work. As the temperatures dropped, a hopeful last crop died overnight in a surprise cold snap right before the onset of Winter. That Winter would be marked by staying indoors and doing as much research as possible - unlocking the next tier of technologies, Mushinto being a jerk to both other women in the colony, Ceti befrending a couple turkeys and a Muffalo, and the colonists surviving in the warmth of their heaters. Now would be a good time to mention that the colony had a hybrid solar/wind/battery electrical system that provided a 24-hour clean and renewable electricity supply with two massive battery backups that could go several days discharging. Alas, this electricity would be the beginning of the end. A freak short circuit on a single strand of wire in the outdoor refridgerator caused a massive fire that immediately burned the entire outdoor supply of potatoes and rice. Mushinto was the first on the scene, trying desperately to stamp out the fire, not realizing that the interior of the outdoor fridge rapidly heated to over 200C. He would die from his wounds in a matter of minutes, with Diver frantically trying to rescue him as Ceti was already dragging a wounded Lowe back to his bed. This left the colonists with only a handful of food, and a dead ally (Diver and Glenn both secretely relieved). Sadly, this would not be the last of the tale of woe. Oh no, what should happen next? A raving pack of exploding rats attacked! Ceti and Glenn set out to kill them, but in their wounded states the rats got to Glenn and wounded her badly. Lowe dragged her inside where he was hiding due to a lack of a weapon and tended to her wounds before grabbing her pistol and going at the exploding buggars. Using a distracting technique, Diver managed to lure a couple rats around the main building where Ceti got a lucky shot and instantly blew up one of the rats. Trapping the other  two in the fire, Ceti and Lowe managed to kill the rest, leaving their corpses out in the open as a grim reminder. Unfortunately, this distraction wounded each of the settlers, and combined with a thick coating of snow, killed off the remaining local wildlife. In a desperate bid to survive a bit longer, the colonists butchered their own turkeys. Rest in Peace, Turkey 1 and Turkey 2, we hardly knew you. Unfortunately, Muffalo 1 was also attacked by a bear a short time later, before she could be milked. On the last day of Winter, we were left with a desperate situation. No food, torrential rains, no wildlife, and a rapidly failing electric grid due to a lack of sun to charge the batery, the colonists were forced to ponder their fate. On the second day of Spring, Ceti snapped and attacked her now husband (married in early Fall) in bed in the middle of the night, Lowe carrying his pistol managed to down her with a gunshot to the arm, and Glenn's knife to Ceti's throat. Miraculously, she survived. Combined with the act of wounding his beloved and a delirious state of malnutrition, Lowe spent a whole day just wandering in the rain and not planting any food. Ceti being wounded, the act of planting was left to Glenn and Diver. Unfortunately they were not enough. On the night of the 4th of Spring, Ceti and Lowe passed away in their sleep of starvation. Glenn would die the next morning, with Diver surviving until the end of the day by desperately feeding off the corpses of her former friends.And that folks, is the story of my first game.10/10 I would absolutely recommend this game if you are into survival and management games like Dwarf Fortress or Banished. This game is quite similar to Banished, but with a futuristic apocalypse setting.Do not let the Early Access fool you, this game is complete enough as is to warrant the $30. I've owned the game for two days and I've put in over 10 hours. It's complete enough for release, but the devs want to add some more stuff. Neat.My only complaint are a few minor issues:* Using right click to drag causes the interface to pup up every time you right click - this shouldn't happen. (it should if you just right click and not drag, but shouldn't when dragging)* The number of rabid animal attacks is quite high for the regular difficulty* If my colonist has a 9/20 gun skill, he shouldn't miss 30 shots in a row against a sleeping beaver. I counted, that actually happened.* Colonists seem to have serious ADHD on the default priorities - maybe tweak the priorities a bit, so colonists will focus on finishing tasks rather than rapidly switching between unrelated tasks. That's a nit-pick, and you can all but avoid it if you set the priorities right."
