76561197982896161,Recommended,294100,29636410,Posted: 1 February,all,Nenvolk,"I love this game :)It's a micro-management basebuilding game, where you control a group of people (it can be a group of one), trying to survive and build a spaceship to get off the planet. To get that far you have to build  a base, collect ressources and build defend the base against hostiles. But I guess you already know this, so I will just do a pro and con list:Pros:-Micromange or Macromanage. You choose how detailed you will control your survivors.-Flexible game. There is alot of potential for Mods, and there are already alot available on Steam Workshop.-Flexible game setup. You can choose several modes, and find more through Steam Workshop. This gives it alot of replayability.-I love that you can give your survivors cyborg arms, legs and eyes. There could be other replacements, like ears, but maybe they will come later :)-All setups are created from XML files (located at Steam\steamapps\common\RimWorld\Mods\Core\Defs). This means if you want rabbits to be super killers you can change their fighting abilities by changing the hitpoints and damage in the XML file, and presto!  Look, that rabbit's got a vicious streak a mile wide! It's a killer! You can also change the value of animals and alot of different things. It is recommended to take a backup of the files you change ;)Con:-Some random events can just end the game. Like dry thunderstorm when you only have 2  survivors, and everything burns down, leaving you with no ressources or base (true story). When you have enough survivors you can fight the fires off, but if not...-Sometimes the random generated map will just create an awful starting place. When this happens I just drop it and starts a new game. Even if it can be fun to play a hard game, it usually means everything takes ALOT of time (for instance if there is almost no steel or almost no components, you need to buy it from friends).-Some of the progress is too dependant of some specific ressources (as mentioned above). It would be cool if there where several paths through the invention tree."
