,Recommended,294100,25508986,"Posted: 15 September, 2016",all,schmnittie,"I, not having a background in sim games in general, definitely stumbled upon a very engrossing game to draw me in to the genre. Rimworld is a game I didn't expect to find myself devoting hours into, but after having my first colony of 6 subjected to the wrath of a distraught cat, Solidarity, it was very hard to simply let that be the end of it.Rimworld is a fickle mistress, both cruel and benevolent at times. A slew of raiders may seem a horrid fate to befall your colony, but may prove your greatest source of income when the pirates wishing to trade the next day appear to have a keen interest in your freshly harvested kidneys, livers, and hearts. Your colonists may be a little bothered, but profit is profit and daddy needs a new bionic arm.At the same time, Rimworld expresses intricate detail and dilligence the more time you put into it. It will oftentimes notify you that family members are raiding you, and you may deem it necessary to have your warden be replaced by the socially inept son of your recently captured couple, that is.. after you provide him with a denture as his jaw was blown off in the preceding ordeal. On top of this another social fight has erupted and your miner is now binging on the equivalent of cocaine because his ex lover insulted him. But hey, with a colony exceeding 30+ there's going to be complications.Ultimately, Rimworld is a game that is very difficult to put down once you've invested any reasonable amount of time, even if only to see yourself fail in a truly fantastic manner."
