76561197966661634,Recommended,294100,24694015,"Posted: 3 August, 2016",all,kingofblahs,"Matthew Clark went berserkReason:  Ate without table10/10On a serious note, Rimworld has the best procedural storytelling of any game I have ever played, and this is a story that I am dealing with at the moment.John, a rich colonist, crashlands on Rimworld with all of his riches and boundless enthusiasm as an explorer.  He specializes in construction and mining, hand picked by myself after looking through many random applicants.  John's life was simple at first.  He found an abandoned slate house which he claimed as his own, only needing to add a door to it to make it complete and save time constructing.John, being as he was brilliant at construction, was quickly able to build defenses and set up most of the power of his colony, but just after completing his defenses, John received a distress call.  Looking at the personality of the person in question, it was deemed that one of them was not worth it, as he was lazy and had no expertise, so John left him to die.   Soon after, we had someone else join our colony in exchange for getting bandits off of his back.  Although Matthew only had mediocre traits, he had just enough for John to accept the invitation, and the invaders were repelled with ease with the defenses John had built up.Not long after, things started to go south, particularly for John.  It all started when we mistakingly gave many of our resources to a surviving refugee that had no interest in joining the colony.  After one day of constant treatment and nurturing, the refugee suddenly left and followed up very quickly by John getting the plague.  After hours of attempted treatment and excruciating pain, John, the original colonist died.  Matthew, who was only intended to do cleaning duties, was now required to do all the work that John once did.  The colony went from a speedy development in efficiency to a true survival situation.  Fortunately, Matthew had great defenses built up and nearly all of the power grid, thus was able to repel all of the raids (and scare the ones he couldn't kill with his charge rifle off).After a couple of days of very little progress, a new colonist joined, Yates, who was far more competent in construction, and the colony started to improve.  The power grid was finished and slowly, we added two bedrooms and a kitchen.But not all was well still.  Matthew continued to mill on about John's death and how he could not take care of him.  Matthew's mood became more and more foul as the days passed, particularly also because food resources were diminishing and the survival meals were no longer there.  Additionally, the colony started to become repulsive because current work didn't allow for cleaning (as there was much else to finish up).We leave off with Matthew going through fits of rage.  Matthew nearly turned on his colonists last night, the only saving grace being as his mental breakdown was after a session of mining, but this also left him without sleep, thus immediately after recovery, he went through another mental breakdown.  This time, however, it's in the actual home, and this is where it leaves off.I doubt I will write the conclusion of this (I will if I think about it), but the point of this is that you can tell rich stories with this game.  The survival elements are there, but the elements combine to tell this emergent story more than any game I have played except for maybe Prison Architect.But, this game is a very different experience than Prison Architect, because Prison Architect is a management game, and this is a survival game.  The steps you take in both games are very different from one another.EDIT://The story finished, with a fitting ending for this game:Matthew went through another mental breakdown, but fortunately nobody was harmed this instant.  He sat in an isolated spot with his gun until he calmed down.  Both breakdowns let out a lot of steam, so for a time, the colony went on normally.  We got the first signs of our kitchen, with at least something to feed us, and things were going well.A new recruit, a pacifist named Chaz joined our camp.  He was fairly decent and well rounded in terms of construction and medicine, so he was worth keeping around.  Unfortunately, he never did get along with Yates, although with a severe infection during the waning hours of the colony, her injuries were treated.Then, the raid came...At first, they seemed like they wanted no part of the defenses.  They wandered about in the northeast part of the area aimlessly.  At the exact same time, Yates father, Jupiter, landed in a pot looking for his daughter.  We decided to take care of him, but in doing so, forgot about the raid just enough to allow the raiders, three with SMGs, one with a grenade luncher, to get close enough.  They attacked the point which had poor turret coverage, and although we had sandbag defenses, because we reacted so late, one of them was able to walk over and do severe damage.The invaders did eventually get defeated ... just.  Yates was dead, Matthew was critically injured, and to compound the situation of already-near mental breakdown, a grenade had exploded near the house, causing a fire.With Matthew incapacitated, Yates dead, and Jupiter not yet being part of the colony, all that was left was the new recruit, Cortez.  Being a pacifist, he was unable to bring himself to fight a fire that likely wouldn't be put out to begin with.  In desperation, two emergency sleeping spots were set up between two abandoned ruin walls where there were few trees to prevent forest fire risk.  Matthew was set down and Cortez went out to collect what supplies he could to at least try to start elsewhere, resigned to the fact that most possessions would be lost.And then the final blow.Jupiter, with his daughter dead and left to burn alive in a fire that there was no time to save him from, got his revenge.  On Cortez way back, he witnessed it perfectly, Matthew being punched to death by Jupiter, in a berserk mental state.Cortez, out of resources, out of options, freezes to death in the night being chased by the raging Jupiter.And this, my friends, is all less than a day of playing RimWorld.  Get this game."
