76561198119437964,Recommended,294100,28682139,"Posted: 26 December, 2016",all,Captain Paradox,"Yeah, I know... I don't have a lot of playtime on this game. I'm going to tell you, however, my opinion thus far and mmaybe I'll edit as I go on and learn new things. Giving you both a fresh and honest prespective early in, and further down the road of sandbags and exploding alien creatures.Day one.RimWorld, is a colony simulator. Infact, it is the perfect colony simulator. Combining all sorts of aspects from survival, to bulding your base and even keeping track of your colonists social interactions with eachother. You must also monitor their moods and needs to ensure no one goes and has a mental breakdown. Make sure everyone is fed, and that your trusty pet companions stay alive. You can have visitors come to your colony at random times. Some are friendly, and some are not. And even the ones who are friendly, you can attack anyway. But watch out for their knives. You can then also capture enemies, and bring them into your colony or sell them. This adds to the survival side of things, you are not just trying to not starve and stay warm, but you need to set up a defense. Some security. However you must also watch out for disasters like fires. My first time playing, a fire started when my colonists were asleep and it spread into a great blaze ingulfing a chunk of the land and was headed for my colony. My colony was on the other side of a hill so I was likely to be okay but my supply storage was on the side closer to the fire. So I tried to beat out the flames but it wasn't good enough. The fire had grown too much. As I said my goodbyes, a miracle presented itself. It rained. Putting out the blaze quickly enough and saving my land. I simply could have ordered my colonists to move the storage supply somewhere else but I'm dumb like that and for some reason never thought of it. But that was in my first game which I am still playing currently and is going well. I can surely say I am enjoying this game beyond measures so far and I highly recommend it to anyone with a taste for survival/building/community management games."
