76561198258614473,Recommended,294100,24786149,"Posted: 8 August, 2016",all,MicroManiac34,"After just over 20 hours of gameplay, I feel comfortable recommending this game to others. It takes a bit of time and patience to get the hang of it, but it is a lot of fun once you’re there. Some things that would help, that I’d like to see in the future of this game’s development:some kind of tutorial to get started, even something simple and light… show the new players some useful hot keysclearer user interface (especially the trade screen, it’s tough at first to see the difference between buying and selling)a clearer difference between hunting and defendinga more complete wiki page for looking things up"
,Recommended,294100,26190703,"Posted: 23 October, 2016",all,Favalava,"Rimworld is a colony management sim where you are responsible for the success of your colony.You will guide colonists as they face raiders, the plague, wild iguanas, fire, aliens and each other. Will they live relatively safe and luxurious lives or will they struggle on the Rimworld?GameplayRimworld is a top down view colony management game. You will control colonists with keyboard and mouse and give them tasks which will, hopefully, be good for the colony. Some people will be better at certain jobs than others and it’s up to you to create efficiency. Through your input, colonists will begin building homes, farming, creating items and researching technology. Every so often you will be attacked by the game’s chosen AI storyteller which will send out enemies to kill you or have your colony plagued by disease or fatal heat waves. The game will play out in real time but will allow you to adjust the game speed and pause the game at will. The base game is about thriving and surviving.PlayerbaseThis game is appealing to different people who enjoy different genres becomes Rimworld combines genres very well. If you have played Grand Strategy, Real Time Strategy, or SIM games then you will find something familiar in Rimworld.Strategy players will find enjoyment in expanding their reach, defending land and developing their empire. Rimworld is really good at making you feel like you're progressing with colony development because of its research system and the technology it rewards.RTS Players will enjoy real time combat, meaningful defensive base development and mastering varying types of warfare. Rimworld has many counters to each weapon and enemy which will allow players who master combat to succeed at higher difficulties.Sim Enthusiasts will enjoy the quirks, traits, relationships and stories that develop around their characters. The game is very good at convincing you that these colonists are different as you begin to understand their strengths, weaknesses and personality.This game is about the stories it creates by setting up mechanisms for happiness and survivalRimWorld has a unique AI storyteller which will change the way you interact with the game and there are different AI's which will cater to the different player genres that RimWorld can accommodate. These function as different playthroughs and difficulties by changing the amount of effort you need to make your colonists happy and the ways you approach combat when protecting them.Developing a colony and focusing your efforts on providing the best a e s t h e t i c for your colonists will make them very happy. Happiness goes a long way in Rimworld because if your people are below a certain threshold they will susceptible to a mental break which will have them be uncontrollable and useless to the colony for a short amount of time. Luxury items will protect your colony from dying from within.Focusing entirely on survival and maintaining only enough luxuries to stop people from going crazy and killing each other is another approach to the game. For some players, a warrior who can protect the colony will always be more useful than a crafter and materials that could be used for defensive fortifications or multiple freezer systems will be better spent there than on art supplies.These two play styles will create their own stories.One can play out as a utopian community focused on opulence which ultimately caused their end by siege of the enemy.The other can be an all work no play colony where the death of a pet could put one person over the edge causing them to start fires everywhere and weaken the colony just before an attack.This game doesn't have a definitive game ending goal and plays out in a sandbox like environment.Even though there isn’t a definitive end or a story like in a single player campaign, the game does present you with an objective that ties into the lore. You crash landed on this Rimworld and you can build a ship to escape back into space but there isn’t a reason to leave whatever civilization you develop. You could even opt to send only the worst of your colonists into space and get rid of the dead weight without guilty down the community.Replayability - Design - SoundFor some people RimWorld will be the only game they buy and play for 2017.This game has insane amount of replayability by offering over 8 biomes with significantly varying degrees of mountain density; point being that you will always have map diversity.The colonist creation process will make you want to find your preferred colonists and you will settle for a doctor who starts fires because that’s better than a sexist drug addict who can’t read.The scenarios that come with the game allow different stories to form around five tribals, three survivors or one really rich dude and these different perspectives will have their own difficulties.Rimworld is a game with an amazing mod community and I highly recommend checking out the mod workshop. The vanilla base game is completely playable and well done and provides more than enough content for a $30 game. Rimworld modders are very creative and offer quality of life improvements as well as full on expansions pack level content. There is even a multiplayer trading network that exists in the mod workshop.The design of RimWorld works well and the top down view of a 2d world doesn’t compromise the gameplay at all. The controls do not feel clunky and are properly labeled which allow you to know exactly what you're doing as you do it but you could just use your mouse 90% of the time.The interface fits 16:9 resolutions well and shouldn't clutter your actual game space.The graphics do enough to distinguish colonists from each other and enemies.The environments look really nice and I have a soft spot for wooden buildings surrounded by fertile grasslands.RimWorld music and sound definitely sticks out to me and I like it. The music is sci-fi western themed and tries to set a mood of exploration and grandiose; which it does pretty well.The sound effects during combat and while cooking, farming, mining, researching, and whatever all do a good job at giving you enough information to know what’s being done and even by who.Even though the game is designed to accommodate more units, machinery, and noise you won’t have to worry about important information cues being drowned out.Reasons To Buy ItThis game really is fun if you’re this kind of person who likes to- chill out and drink coffee while playing a game and/or watching a stream- micromanage colonists and develop an empire- watch relationships develop among virtual people- play games with massive amounts of replayability- to play single player games- play space or sci-fi themed gamesTL;DRRimworld is a great game that you should buy because it’s fun and successfully takes the best parts of other genres and blends them together. At it’s core this a colony management game where you will watch over virtual people. It’s up to you to make this sandbox game rewarding for you and your colonists. If you like a well made video game that offers great replayability and diverse content then this $30 purchase will be for you. So if you enjoy strategy, rts and sim games then you should consider Rimworld as your next library purchase."
76561198052446015,Recommended,294100,33229726,Posted: 4 July,all,Unredeemed™,"Just going to drop this here in addition to the wall of ""Recommended"" reviews.This game is simply put, too good."
76561198166110064,Recommended,294100,33545482,Posted: 14 July,all,Porkchopexpress,"People will often spend around $60 for a good new console game. $40-$60 for a new PC game.This game cost $30 when I purchased it still in early development. I have to say that my choice to spend $30 on this game left me more satisfied than MOST games I would ever would ever buy on console or PC. If I had known that the game had the amount of depth that it did going in...I would have spent more. This game is a bargain.The game is not just another building sim. It is a sim where just trying to make do can resort to cannibalism. It is a sim where an alien race can crash on near your base and try to capture your people as slaves. That alien race may also wish to conduct trade, or offer a helping hand in technology to take out a settlement nearby. One time I ordered my settlers to mine a large area that was high in titanium deposits; they uncovered several hibernation vessels in a great archological find. I was nervous to study them closer...It might have a disease im not prepared for. It might have magical properties. It might be highly advanced. Maybe it is physically strong and proceeds to rip everyone apart....I went for it and out came a few humans. The leader was a cyborg....it was quickly clear that he was forcing the others to attack me. I took out the cyborg and found out the others no longer attacked me. Aparently this cyborg was holding them as slaves; they were as lost as ever so I was excited to find out I had two scientists and an engineer form an advanced civilization aiding me now. Not to mention the cyborg I now get to reverse engineer and collect rare materials from...Something much less similar happened next game after that colony died to some super virus. :(Except that time they were some gigantic worm like alien race who mind controlled the panthers in the jungle I was colonized in to attack my settlement. It was over so fast....those panthers surronded my colony. My turrets could not keep up with the speed and raw amount of them; I think this alien race was also lending them some sort of magical buff or something...because now all the sudden they could tear down walls and crush my electronics/furniture inside. Needless to say all colonists died....This game introduces three main playstyles.- Survivors: 3 crashlanders on a rimworld. With space faring technology, 3 colonists.- Scattered tribesmen: Play as locals who are still in early stages of human tech development. 5 colonists.- Wealthy Expedition: Play as a sole colonist with glitter age tech devolpment and wealthy resources.This is where it all starts....then you realize that colonists come and go all the time. They crash out of the sky. Run in from attemped raids. You buy them as slaves. They attack you and you persuade them to join your cause instead. This doesnt include the MANY animals you can train to breed, fight for you, and haul materials. Or robots. Or whatever the hell else the EXPANSIVE and highly active steam workshop offers.Just a list of the technologies to learn in this game of things off the top of my head: brewing, geothermal power, Robotics, Arcade machines (mod), a\c heat, security turrets, psychoactive drugs, medicines, ai capabilities, blacksmithing, gunsmithing, gardening, hydroponics, transport pods, spaceships....there is more...alot more.Everything about this game is seemingly endless. In the amount of different materials, things you can build, random events that can benefit or jeopardise your colony. A literal ""x"" amount of material if you go through the workshop. Most of the stuff there works quite well also. Train a giant sloth brought back from the prehistoric or so era to carry large amounts of things for you. Train a polar bear to guard your home. Use robots to replace all manual jobs and focus on technology and crafting. Build a heavy military force and gain powerful ally and enemy factions. You can assualt a base and remove a faction permenently. Conduct raids on your rimworld.Guys. This is the ****ing game right here. Im telling you. If you have a bit of patience for this high learning curve game...it has an extraordinary amount of content."
