,Recommended,294100,25042620,"Posted: 20 August, 2016",all,i want to be hit by a train,"Okay, so this is one of the few games I pirated before buying, just because I didn't really want to waste $30 on a game I wouldn't play. And I know about Steam refunds, but I find that I need a bit more than just 2 hours to get full impressions on a game, but that's besides the point.The point is that this game is, to put it simply, bloody fantastic. The level of depth that this game goes into is simply amazing. I won't go into the gameplay that much, because I find it's more fun to discover it for yourself, but I will give you a brief overview of the plot if you play the standard scenario. Three colonists are in cryptosleep, only to be awaken by their ship falling apart. They barely manage to make it to the escape pods, which land on an unknown rimworld. Your job, as a hive-mind commander sort of thing, is to help your colonists survive by giving them indirect (or sometimes direct) orders. Whilst trying to keep your colony alive and happy through random events (good or bad) that occur. These include, but are not limited to: raids, flashstorms, trade caravans and heatwaves. These events are determined by an AI story teller you choose before starting the game, each having different personalities. Depending on how you play this game and what AI you choose, crazy things can happen. As an example, once my colonist, who's son had just died, went on a rampage, shot his cat with a minigun, then ate it.So yea...So if you are a fan of Prison Architect or Dwarf Fortress, then I definitely recommend picking up this game. Even if you aren't a fan of either of those games, still check this game out.""What? You don't make human leather cowboy hats? It's a great market to get into."""
