76561198018723886,Recommended,294100,30255064,Posted: 28 February,all,iNick,"The video and images don't do the game justice.  If you want to see real samples of gameplay - watch a YouTuber.  I spent 2 weeks watching 2 YouTubers  before the week I decided I was going to buy the game.  The let's plays were much more informative, much more enlightening for the game and it's (bluntly said..) depth.  Every moving colonist, animal, mechanoid and even objects like fire and lightning add to a depth of the game that can not be described in words.  Start the game with 1 of 3 scenarios; add a random world generation, from snow to heat to forrests to mountainous terrain (and more probably); add 3 randomized colonists with traits and inabilities (No such thing as a perfect colonist); and one of 3 AI storytellers with each some 5 or so difficulty levels; and set permadeath if you want.  Phew, mouthful - but that's just setting up a save file.  Now you gotta make your colonists survive together, avoid exploding wildlife, take care of health concerns (including surgery), weddings, colonists hating each other, mental breakdowns, umm, this is an endless list.  Then the video on the store page describes raids, traders, orbiting space traders, and..  well, death.  Welcome to RimWorld!"
